  Additive Manufacturing (AM): Machines and Techniques
</div>

Additive manufacturing is a unique process that can create lighter, stronger, and abstract parts that traditional subtractive manufacturing cannot replicate. The most common way of doing this is with a 3D printer. Objects and parts are printed layer by layer out of materials ranging from thermoplastics, metals, ceramics, to biochemicals. The benefits of additive manufacturing include incorporating cellular structures, manufacturing joints and parts as a single piece for rapid assembly, and quick prototyping to rapidly iterate and test parts. Learn more about the benefits and applications of additive manufacturing on the interactive screens to the right and left! <br>

With the advent of faster and inexpensive controllers, additive manufacturing has become an incredibly accessible technology and modern convenience available to everyone. Furthermore, additive manufacturing is a developing technology and has multiple different styles and processes that all fall under the larger umbrella of “additive manufacturing” itself. Below a few different types are broken out and explained. <br>


<button class="w3-button cm-button" onclick="expand('fdm')"> // Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) // </button>
<div id="fdm" class="w3-container w3-round-large cm-acordian w3-hide">
  Fused Deposition Modeling, more typically called FDM, is the process of converting a computer generated model into a physical object by depositing molten plastics layer by layer to form the final product. FDM is the most common form of additive manufacturing currently because of its simplicity and low cost. <br>
